******
[6] Germany, Berlin
Date: Sat 21 May 2022
Source: DW [abridged, edited]
https://www.dw.com/en/monkeypox-berlin-records-first-cases-of-rare-virus/a-61889401


In the German capital, 2 people have tested positive for monkeypox a day after Munich registered its 1st case. A surprise outbreak of the rare infectious disease has spread from Europe to the US and the Middle East.

At least 2 people have tested positive for monkeypox in Berlin, authorities said on Saturday [21 May 2022], warning that more cases would likely emerge over the next few days.

The rare infectious disease, which causes distinctive pustules but is rarely fatal, is endemic to parts of Central and Western Africa.

In recent weeks, more than 100 confirmed or suspected cases have been recorded in Europe, as well as the United States, Canada, and Australia.

Health officials in Berlin said the 2 patients were in stable condition. Efforts had begun to trace their contacts.

Public broadcaster RBB said at least one patient was thought to have been infected at a Berlin club.

It is unclear which of the 2 groups (or "clades") of the virus the 2 patients have contracted.

So far, all of the cases registered in Europe are of the milder West African group, rather than the more severe Central African one.

